Bay Wheels May 2020 Trip Data Analysis¶

by Yi Wang¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The data under analysis is the Bay Wheels trip history data. Bay wheel trip provides bike share service as a new transportation option in Bay area, USA. They have deployed a number of stations and bikes throughout San Francisco, the East Bay, and San Jose. Besides the traditional docked bikes, Bay Wheels introduces ebikes during 2019 November. A rider needs to download an APP called Lyft and scan the QR code on the bike when start using it and then return it back to one of the stations when the trip ends. Rider can pay by monthly/yearly membership fee or per ride. This report focuses on the data gathered during May 2020.

Assessment¶

  • Null values for the following columns: start_station_name, start_station_id, end_station_name, end_station_id, end_lat, end_lng
  • start_station_id and end_station_id column data type is float rather than object
  • started_at and ended_at column data type is object rather than datetime
  • member_casual and rideable_type column data type is object rather than category
  • the ended_at time is earlier than started_at time in some rows
  • The end time is beyond the start time for some rows
  • In some rows, the start_lat / start_lng and end_lat / end_lng remain the same with less than 10s using time. This indicates the user didn't ride the bike and stopped using the service after a very short time.

Define¶

Use the start latitude / longitude and end latitude / longitude to calculate the distance a user travels.

Code¶

In [27]:
# calculate the circle distance between two points on the earth using latitude and longitude value
def calculate_distance(lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2):
    lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2 = map(np.radians, [lon1, lat1, lon2, lat2])

    dlon = lon2 - lon1
    dlat = lat2 - lat1

    a = np.sin(dlat/2.0)**2 + np.cos(lat1) * np.cos(lat2) * np.sin(dlon/2.0)**2

    c = 2 * np.arcsin(np.sqrt(a))
    km = 6367 * c
    return km
In [28]:
# calculate the circle distance between the start point and end point and use its value to create a new column called distance
df_clean['distance'] = calculate_distance(df_clean['start_lat'], df_clean['start_lng'], df_clean['end_lat'], df_clean['end_lng'])

# round to two digits after decimal
df_clean['distance'] = df_clean['distance'].round(2);

Findings of data wrangling¶

The data after cleaning includes 20 columns and 70679 rows. Six of the columns are newly added during data cleaning. They are start_weekday_name, start_hour, end_weekday_name, end_hour, duration and distance. Among the columns, there are 1 boolean, 4 category, 2 datatime, 5 float, 3 integer and 5 object.

The main feature of interest in the dataset is the distribution of rides across different days of week and different time. This helps us understand when riders use this service across the time. Another one is how the rides of traditional docked bikes differ from that of ebikes.

The following columns will be focused to support the investigation:

  • rideable_type
  • start_weekday_name
  • start_hour
  • member_casual
  • duration
  • distance

Findings of univariate exploration¶

The distribution of rides across the hour of a day is a right-skewed one with peak at around 17 o'clock. The number of rides distributes evenly from Monday to Thursday with a rise on Friday and weekends.

Besides, the distribution of rides based on duration is a left-skewed one with the peak at around 6 - 7 min. When plotting this histogram I noticed two peaks after initial plotting. After taking a closer look at it, I noticed there are several records with less than 10s duration and 0-0.01 km distance which indicates the rider didn't really start the trip. So I went back to cleaning phase and removed these invalid data for plotting purpose.

I noticed there are negative duration when plotting the histogram of duration. The duration indicates the period of time a bike is rent so it should be positive. So I went back to the cleaning step to remove rows where duration is negative. Besides, the initial unit of duration was minute. However, I noticed that most of the distribution are narrowed to a single bar in histogram. So I went back to cleaning phase and changed the unit to seconds.

Question: How do duration and distance correlate to each other?¶

In [50]:

In [72]:
# plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(8,5))
plt.scatter(data=df_clean_common, x='duration', y='distance', alpha=.5)
plt.title ('Duration vs. Distance');

The scatter plot above indicates the relationship of duration and distance is not always linear. The straight edge on the left side of this plot indicates, for some users, the distance increases linearly as the duration increases. However, a large amount of dots indicates the duration may increase while the distance keeps small. This fact tells us the user may rent the bike for a period of time but not necessarily always use it during this time.

Findings of bivariate exploration¶

For both members and customers, the peak hour of using the service is 17 o'clock and either 3 or 4 o'clock is the most silent time. More members than customers are using the service during 4 - 9 and 23 o'clock while the opposite for the rest of time. More members use the service than customers during weekdays while it attracts more customers than members during weekends.

The average duration of renting a ebike is less than that of a docked-bike. There are less users using both types of bikes during weekdays than weekends. Besides, 17 o'clock is the peak hour of using both types of bikes while 3 o'clock is the most silent time. It is interesting to notice the usage of ebikes is almost the same or over that of docked-bikes during 6 - 8 o'clock which is the time of start working for most people.

Moreover, the peak hour of using the service is 17 o'clock during weekdays but before 15 o'clock during weekends. Midnight, between 2 -4 o'clock is the most silent time for this service.

There is a strong linear relationship between the start hour and end hour of riding a bike which makes sense since the end hour is always after the start hour. The start position and end position also has a relationship. Besides, the duration and distance is related to each other linearly only for some riders but not necessarily for all riders.

Findings of multivariate exploration¶

Compared to that of customers, the average riding duration varies less for members everyday. Generally speaking, the average riding duration is less for members than that of customers on both weekdays and weekends. Besides, riders with ebikes generally tend to travel farer away during the same period of time. But renting an ebike does not always lead a rider to travel farer.

Summary¶

The data of May 2020 is analyzed and visualized after being cleaned. Here are the main findings based on the analysis:

  • There are more rides during weekends than weekdays
  • The most common duration of renting the bike is 6 to 7 minutes.
  • 17 o'clock is the peak of using the service while the midnight is the most silent one.
  • Members rides more than customers during weekdays while the service attracts more customers than members during weekends.
  • The peak hour of this service is 17 o'clock during weekdays but before 15 o'clock during weekends.
  • More members than customers use the service during morning (4-9 o'clock) time while more customers use it during day time.
  • For both members and customers, the peak hour of riding is 17 o'clock.
  • Both ebikes and docked-bikes attract more riders during weekends than weekdays.
  • The peak hour of rides is 17 o'clock for both ebikes and docked-bikes.
  • The rides of ebikes is almost the same or even higher than that of docked bikes during early morning (6-8 o'clock).
  • The average duration of riding ebikes varies less than that of docked bikes in different days of week.
